x4freetext: Pulsed 5.5-MeV Van de Graaff.
Protons on tritium
Cylinder 2.54-cm diameter by 5-cm high containing
2.85-moles of elemental cobalt
40-cm**3 germanium-lithium crystal surrounded
by lead rings embedded in lithium carbonate and
paraffin to reduce background gammas. Shielded from
direct neu- trons by copper shadow bar.
Hansen-McKibben long counter for neutron
flux. Calibrated below 2-MeV with known protons on
tritium cross sections and above 2-MeV with Los
Alamos type proton recoil telescope. Calibrations
matched at overlap.
Plastic scintillator with photomultiplier.
Used to normalize long counter. Has unobstructed view
of tritium target at all times.
Corrected for multiple scattering and neutron and
gamma attenuation
Errors include uncertainties due to:
absolute zero-degree neutron flux uncertainty
Ge(Li) detector efficiency (4%),
uncertainty of finite sample
corrections and variation of neutron flux through
sample corrections (1.5 - 5%),
extraction of areas of full energy
peaks, including statistical errors (5 - 30%).
Tabulated data received from J.Egan, 1977/6.
approved by J.W.Egan, 1979/7/3.

x4freetext: Time-gated Ge(Li) detector energy spectrum.
Neutron flux measured with sample out of the beam
after each run. gamma-ray excitation functions were
measured at 90 and 125 degrees from 1.11 to 3.32 MeV.
gamma-ray angular distributions for the stronger
transitions were measured at 1.41, 1.76, 1.91, 2.32,
and 2.82 MeV. The pulsed-beam time-of-flight
technique was employed for background reduction.

x4freetext: The integral gamma-ray production cross sections were
obtained by fitting each of the angular distributions
with a series of Legendre polynomials. This provided
accurate cross sections for those bombarding energies
and transitions for which complete angular
distributions were available. At energies other than
the five mentioned in subentry 2 and for the weaker
transitions the 125 deg excitation function data were
used in obtaining the integrated cross sections.
Also shown in Figs. 6-7, pages 1192-1193
